03918nam a22005895i 9780292734692DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212011txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927346927 a10.7560/7239482doi  a(DE-B1597)587401  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 7aPER0000002bisacsh04a792.093851 aRoselli, David Kawalko, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTheater of the People :bSpectators and Society in Ancient Athens /cDavid Kawalko Roselli. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (302 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tConventions and Abbreviations Used -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction. Theater and People in At hens -- tChapter 1. The Idea of the Audience and Its Role in the Theater -- tChapter 2. Space and Spectators in the Theater -- tChapter 3. The Economics of the Theater: Theoric Distributions and Class Divisions -- tChapter 4. Noncitizens in the Theater -- tChapter 5. Women and the Theater Audience -- tEpilogue -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex Locorum -- tGeneral Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aGreek drama has been subject to ongoing textual and historical interpretation, but surprisingly little scholarship has examined the people who composed the theater audiences in Athens. Typically, scholars have presupposed an audience of Athenian male citizens viewing dramas created exclusively for themselves—a model that reduces theater to little more than a medium for propaganda. Women's theater attendance remains controversial, and little attention has been paid to the social class and ethnicity of the spectators. Whose theater was it? Producing the first book-length work on the subject, David Kawalko Roselli draws on archaeological and epigraphic evidence, economic and social history, performance studies, and ancient stories about the theater to offer a wide-ranging study that addresses the contested authority of audiences and their historical constitution. Space, money, the rise of the theater industry, and broader social forces emerge as key factors in this analysis. In repopulating audiences with foreigners, slaves, women, and the poor, this book challenges the basis of orthodox interpretations of Greek drama and places the politically and socially marginal at the heart of the theater. Featuring an analysis of the audiences of Aeschylus, Sophocles, Euripides, Aristophanes, and Menander, Theater of the People brings to life perhaps the most powerful influence on the most prominent dramatic poets of their day.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 7aPERFORMING ARTS / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/72394840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292734692423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292734692/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK